✅ Option 1 — Use the Software Catalog (Lowest risk)

What

Store data as metadata (annotations/labels) in the catalog

Use for

request_id, request_category, status (lightweight tracking)

Why

No database work
Fully supported in Backstage
Zero risk to the core DB

Plain rule

“If it’s simple tracking data, use the catalog—no tables needed.”

✅ Option 2 — Custom plugin with its own schema (Recommended default)

What

Create tables inside your plugin, in your own schema

Use for

Workflow data, approvals, audit logs, anything dynamic

Why

Safe for Red Hat Developer Hub core DB
Clear ownership boundary
Standard Backstage pattern

Plain rule

“You get your own space in the DB—only use that space.”

✅ Option 3 — Separate database (Safest isolation)

What

Your plugin uses a completely separate Postgres database

Use for

Critical systems
Growing or long-term applications

Why

Zero chance of impacting RHDH database
Full control and isolation

Plain rule

“If it’s important or growing, use your own database.”

🚫 Always prohibited (keep this clear)
Do NOT modify or write to RHDH core tables
Do NOT use psql to insert/update data directly
Do NOT read from internal tables (catalog, entities, etc.)
🧭 Simple recommendation to give them

“Start with a plugin using your own schema.
Use the catalog for simple metadata.
Move to a separate database if this becomes critical.”
